## Hexadecimal Representation of Binary Data

When we look at the binary data, it is usually displayed in hexadecimal format. This is because it is easier to read and understand hexadecimal numbers than binary numbers. Each hexadecimal digit represents 4 bits, which is half of a byte.

```js

```

Only the middle part is actual data, the other parts are generated by hex.nvim as metadata for displaying the data.

The intermediate data is displayed in hexadecimal, but the original data content is actually in binary. hex.nvim automatically converts each byte(8 bits) into two hexadecimal characters(4 bits each).

On the right side is the `decoded text`, which is the result of converting each byte into ASCII characters. It usually doesn't make sense to us unless it is actually used to store text data, then we will see meaningful text.

You can see each row is 16 bytes(128 bits) long. But the actual data has no table or row structure. It is just for displaying purposes.
